project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG020825%2F1"><gtr:id>C8EA0957-B0B6-4CB4-B588-88EE6F6206CB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Threshold Regression Models in Dynamic Heterogeneous Panels</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G020825/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The research project proposes the rigorous investigation of nonlinear mechanisms within a dynamic heterogeneous panel setting when the number of time periods is small relative to the number of cross-section units. The relative absence of studies in this area is surprising, considering the well-established literatures on GMM and bias-corrected estimation of linear dynamic panels, and time series regime-switching models. So this project aims to fill this gap by addressing the joint issue as how best to model asymmetric mechanisms and cross-sectional heterogeneity. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project focuses on threshold regression models in dynamic panels, and advances two alternative methodologies: an extended GMM estimation and an iterative bootstrap-based bias corrected estimation procedure. The proposed framework can be extended in several dimensions including a threshold error correction model in dynamic panels, which is characterised by the common long-run relationship and the regime-dependent short-run dynamics. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The project will develop the associated asymptotic theory and the sub-sampling-based inference for deriving (non-standard) sampling distribution theory. The small sample performance will be evaluated via stochastic simulations. We then apply the proposed techniques to a variety of applications in Economics and Finance, eg testing the validity of alternative theories of the capital structure and redressing the growth convergence literature.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-11-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-12-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>66056</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/B5984EBA-1192-4853-8085-065D56762139"><gtr:id>B5984EBA-1192-4853-8085-065D56762139</gtr:id><gtr:title>Probabilistic forecasting of output growth, inflation and the balance of trade in a GVAR framework</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Applied Econometrics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/6591c27369de53779ba779b555fb67da"><gtr:id>6591c27369de53779ba779b555fb67da</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Greenwood-Nimmo M</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-000-22-3161</gtr:id